	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Not touching the legal stuff, it affects the quality and appeal of the game. First, people will recognize the graphics very fast, and it define their feeling about the game, something like 'a non-serious homebrew'. It especially will happen if you take all the graphics from a single game, some may even consider your game a hack in the result. Second, if you take graphics from different games, you'll end up with the problem of unmatching styles, which easily could give the game unprofessional look even if good pieces of graphics were used.
<br />
<br />Other thoughts - if you borrow graphics from other game, why not go further? Get music and sounds too, then code, then story.
<br />
<br />Regarding Dizzy games specifically, there were a lot of fan-made Dizzy games on ZX Spectrum, and for me the best ones back then were those that had at least some new, original graphics - that made them 'fresh' and more interesting.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


